Note: ========================================
Note: HIR to ARM Generator
Note: ========================================
Note: Generates valid ARM assembly (ARMv7/ARMv8) from HIR
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Produces ARM-compatible assembler output
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/arm/arm_emitter.runa" as Emitter
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the HIR -> ARM assembly backend. Verifies the HIR
dictionary carries the expected "type" sentinel before doing any work, so
callers that route HIR through multiple backends do not produce garbage
when the root does not target ARM.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds an emitter, reads hir["type"] and aborts (destroying the emitter)
unless it is the string "arm_assembly". Then emits labels, directives, and
instructions in that fixed order. Returns the snapshot output pointer
allocated by the emitter; caller owns it.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(L + D + I) where L, D, I are the lengths of the labels, directives and
instructions lists. Each list is walked exactly once.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Trusts the HIR dictionary structure produced upstream. A non-matching
"type" sentinel is rejected by returning 0 rather than emitting partial
output.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "generate_arm_from_hir" takes hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main entry point - generate ARM assembly from HIR dictionary

    If hir is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let emitter be proc create_arm_emitter from Emitter

    Note: Verify this is an ARM assembly HIR
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc get from Dict with hir, type_key
    If type_value is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_arm_emitter from Emitter with emitter
        Return 0
    End If

    Let type_str be type_value
    Let is_arm be proc string_equals with type_str, "arm_assembly"
    If is_arm is not equal to 1:
        proc destroy_arm_emitter from Emitter with emitter
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Generate labels
    Let labels_key be proc create_string_literal with "labels"
    Let labels be proc get from Dict with hir, labels_key
    If labels is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_labels with emitter, labels
    End If

    Note: Generate directives
    Let directives_key be proc create_string_literal with "directives"
    Let directives be proc get from Dict with hir, directives_key
    If directives is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_directives with emitter, directives
    End If

    Note: Generate instructions
    Let instructions_key be proc create_string_literal with "instructions"
    Let instructions be proc get from Dict with hir, instructions_key
    If instructions is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_instructions with emitter, instructions
    End If

    Let output be proc get_output from Emitter with emitter
    proc destroy_arm_emitter from Emitter with emitter
    Return output
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit each label definition at column 0. ARM labels are not indented in
canonical assembler output so they remain visually distinct from
instructions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the labels list, reads each entry's "name" field, emits the name
followed by ":" and LF. Entries with no "name" key are silently skipped
so partially-constructed HIR does not abort generation.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_labels" takes emitter as Integer, labels as Integer:
    Note: Generate label definitions

    Let label_count be proc size from List with labels
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than label_count:
        Let label_hir be proc get from List with labels, i

        Note: Get label name
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        Let name_value be proc get from Dict with label_hir, name_key
        If name_value is not equal to 0:
            Let name_str be name_value
            proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, name_str
            proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 58  Note: :
            proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit ARM assembler directives (.section, .global, .word, ...). Directives
take comma-separated argument lists; centralising their emission keeps the
spacing/comma layout consistent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the directives list. For each directive emits the "name" verbatim,
then a space, then comma-separated arguments produced by recursing through
generate_operand. Closes with a newline. Missing arguments list is
tolerated and emits no operands.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_directives" takes emitter as Integer, directives as Integer:
    Note: Generate assembler directives

    Let directive_count be proc size from List with directives
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than directive_count:
        Let directive_hir be proc get from List with directives, i

        Note: Get directive name
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        Let name_value be proc get from Dict with directive_hir, name_key
        If name_value is not equal to 0:
            Let name_str be name_value
            proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, name_str
        End If

        Note: Generate directive arguments
        Let args_key be proc create_string_literal with "arguments"
        Let arguments be proc get from Dict with directive_hir, args_key
        If arguments is not equal to 0:
            Let arg_count be proc size from List with arguments
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than arg_count:
                proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 32  Note: Space
                Let arg be proc get from List with arguments, j
                proc generate_operand with emitter, arg
                If j is less than arg_count minus 1:
                    proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 44  Note: ,
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If

        proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit the body of a function or section. Each instruction is indented one
level, written mnemonic-then-operands, and terminated with a newline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the instructions list. For each instruction emits one level of
indentation (4 spaces) via emit_indent, then "mnemonic", then a space and
comma-separated operands when present. Lists with no operands omit the
trailing space.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_instructions" takes emitter as Integer, instructions as Integer:
    Note: Generate ARM assembly instructions

    Let instr_count be proc size from List with instructions
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than instr_count:
        Let instr_hir be proc get from List with instructions, i

        Note: Indent instruction
        proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, 1

        Note: Get instruction mnemonic
        Let mnemonic_key be proc create_string_literal with "mnemonic"
        Let mnemonic_value be proc get from Dict with instr_hir, mnemonic_key
        If mnemonic_value is not equal to 0:
            Let mnemonic_str be mnemonic_value
            proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, mnemonic_str
        End If

        Note: Generate operands
        Let operands_key be proc create_string_literal with "operands"
        Let operands be proc get from Dict with instr_hir, operands_key
        If operands is not equal to 0:
            Let operand_count be proc size from List with operands
            If operand_count is greater than 0:
                proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 32  Note: Space
            End If

            Let j be 0
            While j is less than operand_count:
                Let operand be proc get from List with operands, j
                proc generate_operand with emitter, operand
                If j is less than operand_count minus 1:
                    proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 44  Note: ,
                    proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 32  Note: Space
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If

        proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the seven ARM operand kinds (register, immediate, memory,
register_list, shifted, identifier, and an implicit fallthrough). Routing
by string discriminator keeps the operand subgrammar open-ended for
future ARM extensions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads operand["type"], converts to a C-string, and probes each known kind
with string_equals. The first match dispatches to its generate_* helper.
Unknown types emit nothing (silent failure) so HIR additions do not break
emission of valid sibling operands.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_operand" takes emitter as Integer, operand as Integer:
    Note: Generate ARM assembly operand

    If operand is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc get from Dict with operand, type_key
    If type_value is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let type_str be type_value

    Let is_register be proc string_equals with type_str, "register"
    If is_register is equal to 1:
        proc generate_register with emitter, operand
        Return
    End If

    Let is_immediate be proc string_equals with type_str, "immediate"
    If is_immediate is equal to 1:
        proc generate_immediate with emitter, operand
        Return
    End If

    Let is_memory be proc string_equals with type_str, "memory"
    If is_memory is equal to 1:
        proc generate_memory with emitter, operand
        Return
    End If

    Let is_register_list be proc string_equals with type_str, "register_list"
    If is_register_list is equal to 1:
        proc generate_register_list with emitter, operand
        Return
    End If

    Let is_shifted be proc string_equals with type_str, "shifted"
    If is_shifted is equal to 1:
        proc generate_shifted with emitter, operand
        Return
    End If

    Let is_identifier be proc string_equals with type_str, "identifier"
    If is_identifier is equal to 1:
        proc generate_identifier with emitter, operand
        Return
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Register operand emission. Register name comes from HIR pre-validated by
the ARM parser, so this function only needs to write it verbatim.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads register["name"], converts to C-string, emits the string. Missing
name field emits nothing rather than aborting.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_register" takes emitter as Integer, register as Integer:
    Note: Generate register operand (r0-r15, sp, lr, pc, etc.)

    Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
    Let name_value be proc get from Dict with register, name_key
    If name_value is not equal to 0:
        Let name_str be name_value
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, name_str
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit ARM immediate operands with the "#" prefix required by GNU as and
ARMv7/v8 syntax (e.g. mov r0, #42).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits '#' (byte 35), then the operand's "value" field as a verbatim
string. The HIR stores the value as a pre-formatted string so this
function avoids re-formatting decisions about base.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_immediate" takes emitter as Integer, immediate as Integer:
    Note: Generate immediate value (#123)

    proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 35  Note: #

    Let value_key be proc create_string_literal with "value"
    Let value_str_obj be proc get from Dict with immediate, value_key
    If value_str_obj is not equal to 0:
        Let value_str be value_str_obj
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, value_str
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Memory reference syntax for ARM: "[base]", "[base, offset]", optionally
suffixed with "!" for writeback. Recurses into generate_operand for the
offset so register-, immediate-, and shifted-offsets all share emission.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits '[', then the base register name (raw string at "base"), optionally
emits ", " followed by generate_operand on the "offset" sub-dictionary,
emits ']', then emits '!' (byte 33) if "writeback" is present.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_memory" takes emitter as Integer, memory as Integer:
    Note: Generate memory reference [base, offset]

    proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 91  Note: [

    Note: Generate base register
    Let base_key be proc create_string_literal with "base"
    Let base_value be proc get from Dict with memory, base_key
    If base_value is not equal to 0:
        Let base_str be base_value
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, base_str
    End If

    Note: Generate offset (if present)
    Let offset_key be proc create_string_literal with "offset"
    Let offset_value be proc get from Dict with memory, offset_key
    If offset_value is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 44  Note: ,
        proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 32  Note: Space
        proc generate_operand with emitter, offset_value
    End If

    proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 93  Note: ]

    Note: Generate writeback indicator (if present)
    Let writeback_key be proc create_string_literal with "writeback"
    Let writeback_value be proc get from Dict with memory, writeback_key
    If writeback_value is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 33  Note: !
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM ldm/stm instructions take brace-enclosed register lists like
{r0-r3, lr}. Each register in the list is emitted as a normal register
operand so range-collapsed forms (r0-r3) must already be present in HIR.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits '{', then a comma-separated walk over the "registers" list via
generate_operand, then '}'. Missing list emits "{}" which is technically
invalid; upstream HIR validation is expected to prevent this.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_register_list" takes emitter as Integer, register_list as Integer:
    Note: Generate register list {r0-r3, lr}

    proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 123  Note: {

    Let registers_key be proc create_string_literal with "registers"
    Let registers be proc get from Dict with register_list, registers_key
    If registers is not equal to 0:
        Let reg_count be proc size from List with registers
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than reg_count:
            Let register be proc get from List with registers, i
            proc generate_operand with emitter, register
            If i is less than reg_count minus 1:
                proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 44  Note: ,
                proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 32  Note: Space
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 125  Note: }
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM shifted-register operands are written "Rn, <shift_op> <amount>" (e.g.
"r1, lsl #2"). The shift operand is part of the same comma-separated
position as the source register; the shift_op and amount form a separate
mini-grammar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the base register operand via generate_operand. If "shift_op" is
present, emits ", " then the op mnemonic; if "shift_amount" is present,
emits a space then recurses into generate_operand for the amount.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_shifted" takes emitter as Integer, shifted as Integer:
    Note: Generate shifted operand (r1, lsl #2)

    Note: Generate base register
    Let register_key be proc create_string_literal with "register"
    Let register_value be proc get from Dict with shifted, register_key
    If register_value is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_operand with emitter, register_value
    End If

    Note: Generate shift operator
    Let shift_op_key be proc create_string_literal with "shift_op"
    Let shift_op_value be proc get from Dict with shifted, shift_op_key
    If shift_op_value is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 44  Note: ,
        proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 32  Note: Space
        Let shift_op_str be shift_op_value
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, shift_op_str
    End If

    Note: Generate shift amount
    Let shift_amt_key be proc create_string_literal with "shift_amount"
    Let shift_amt_value be proc get from Dict with shifted, shift_amt_key
    If shift_amt_value is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_char from Emitter with emitter, 32  Note: Space
        proc generate_operand with emitter, shift_amt_value
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Label/symbol references in operand position. Used by branch instructions
("b loop", "bl my_function") and by data directives.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads identifier["name"], converts to C-string, emits it.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_identifier" takes emitter as Integer, identifier as Integer:
    Note: Generate identifier (label reference or symbol)

    Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
    Let name_value be proc get from Dict with identifier, name_key
    If name_value is not equal to 0:
        Let name_str be name_value
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, name_str
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Local C-string equality so the ARM backend does not need to take a
dependency on StringCore's equality helper - the comparison runs against
type discriminator strings that are short and ASCII-only.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Byte-by-byte loop comparing memory_get_byte at increasing offsets.
Returns 0 on first mismatch, 1 when both reach the shared NUL terminator
at the same index.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in shared prefix length. Used in tight dispatch loops; the small
fixed set of discriminator strings keeps n tiny.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Both inputs must be null-terminated. Non-terminated buffers cause an
infinite loop and read out-of-bounds. All call sites here pass either
HIR-derived or compile-time-literal strings.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "string_equals" takes str1 as String, str2 as String returns Integer:
    Note: Compare two null-terminated strings for equality

    Let i be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str1, i
        Let c2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str2, i
        If c1 is not equal to c2:
            Return 0
        End If
        If c1 is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convenience renaming of StringCore.create_from_literal so dispatch
sites read more naturally.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single-line forward to StringCore.create_from_literal. The returned
pointer follows StringCore's ownership rules.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DISPATCHER ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-arg wrapper matching the shape that translation.runa's central
HIR -> target dispatcher expects: `proc hir_to_arm from ArmEmitter
with hir_root`. Delegates to generate_arm_from_hir which owns the
full pipeline (emitter creation, HIR walking, code generation,
cleanup). The null guard matches the convention used by every other
emitter wrapper so a null HIR root returns 0 rather than crashing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to generate_arm_from_hir(hir_root) verbatim after a single
null-pointer short-circuit. The underlying entry point already
returns a caller-owned output string pointer (or 0 on failure),
matching the dispatcher's Integer-pointer return contract.
@End Implementation

Process called "hir_to_arm" takes hir_root as Integer returns Integer:
    If hir_root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc generate_arm_from_hir with hir_root
End Process
